pullRequest.body:
Define a complex-valued moment generating function and prove that it is holomorphic.
As a consequence, the moment generating function is analytic on the interior of the interval on which it is finite.

Thanks!
Maybe this should also be expressed with `integrableExpSet`?

```suggestion
    simpa only [Complex.norm_eq_abs, Complex.abs_exp, mul_re, add_re, ofReal_re, add_im, ofReal_im,
      mul_zero, sub_zero]
```
This also works, feel free to change it or not.
At many places you wrote `convexMGF` instead of `complexMGF`, is it intended?
No it's definitely not intended. It's a typo I make quite often.
Isn't `have` better here?
tagging `Complex.continuous_abs` with `fun_prop` solves it.
`rw` works fine here.

```suggestion
/-- If two random variables have the same moment generating function then they have
the same `integrableExpSet`. -/
```

Shouldn't these go in `Probability.Moments.Basic`? These lemmas do not need `complexMGF`. I know `integrableExpSet` is not imported there because the integrability assumptions on the exponential are plainly written. Is it because `integrableExpSet` is supposed to be used only when we want to talk about the set of values, but not when we are only using one particular value?

They are here because of import reasons as you guessed: I defined `integrableExpSet` in the `integrableExpMul` file, which does not import and is not imported by `Moments.Basic`.

My idea was indeed to use `integrableExpSet` only when I need to talk about several points and otherwise simply use `Integrable`.

Sorry if this is naive, but in the case where `integrableExpSet` has nonempty interior, can't we say that the two variables have the same distribution (though this result is not in Mathlib I think), and thus `complexMGF` will coincide everywhere because it only depends on the distribution? That would answer the question.

The todo is worded badly: I indeed know that complexMGF will be the same everywhere because the distributions will be equal (at least I know it in the finite measure case).
But the proof I have in mind for [equal mgf => equal distributions] is [equal mgf => equal complexMGF on a domain containing the vertical line going through 0 => equal characteristic functions => equal distributions]. The todo is asking whether we can prove the equality of complexMGF directly, at that point, without "fancy" things like [equal mgf => equal distributions].

Ok, unless I am mistaken I think dominated convergence theorem gives convergence of the complex mgf along horizontal lines when the variable is integrable on the vertical line, which would yield the equality.
I think I will leave it as it is for now, as I don't really need the equality everywhere and would prefer to work on other things.

Maybe it would be nice to factor that out with a lemma saying that 
```
example (hz : z.re âˆˆ integrableExpSet X Î¼) : Integrable (fun Ï‰ â†¦ cexp (z * X Ï‰)) Î¼
```
with something similar for X^n exp(zX)

You can make this more general:
```suggestion
@[simp]
lemma coeff_ofScalars {ð•œ : Type*} [NontriviallyNormedField ð•œ] {p : â„• â†’ ð•œ} {n : â„•} :
    (ofScalars ð•œ p).coeff n = p n := by
  simp [coeff, ofScalars, List.prod_ofFn]
```
Also I think the place you put it previously (just after the definition of `ofScalars`) was good, it looks to me as an obvious lemma which should be stated right away (even though nobody ever needed it apparently).
I moved it closer to the definition, but after the basic API lemmas about zero.

You can generalize to an `RCLike` field without touching the proof, though that requires importing `RCLike`. So maybe it's better to move this to `Mathlib.Analysis.Calculus.IteratedDeriv.Lemmas`?
```suggestion
lemma AnalyticAt.hasFPowerSeriesAt {ð•œ : Type*} [RCLike ð•œ] {f : ð•œ â†’ ð•œ} {x : ð•œ}
    (h : AnalyticAt ð•œ f x) :
    HasFPowerSeriesAt f
      (FormalMultilinearSeries.ofScalars ð•œ (fun n â†¦ iteratedDeriv n f x / n.factorial)) x := by
```

There is no `RCLike` in the file Lemmas either. In the end I did not move it, and generalized it to
`{ð•œ : Type*} [NontriviallyNormedField ð•œ] [CompleteSpace ð•œ] [CharZero ð•œ]`
(whatever those `ð•œ` actually are)

I was under the impression that the number of declarations in `Defs` files should be minimal. If you don't think it's important feel free to ignore this.
> (whatever those `ð•œ` actually are)

Yes I wondered that too so I didn't do the generalization in the end ðŸ˜†

```suggestion
lemma integrable_cexp_mul_of_re_mem_interior_integrableExpSet
    (hz : z.re âˆˆ interior (integrableExpSet X Î¼)) :
    Integrable (fun Ï‰ â†¦ cexp (z * X Ï‰)) Î¼ := by
  have hX : AEMeasurable X Î¼ := aemeasurable_of_mem_interior_integrableExpSet hz
  exact integrable_cexp_mul_of_re_mem_integrableExpSet hX (interior_subset hz)
```
You can even make it a one-liner if you want.

```suggestion
  have h_int_mul i : Integrable (fun Ï‰ â†¦ X Ï‰ ^ i * cexp (z * X Ï‰)) Î¼ :=
    integrable_pow_mul_cexp_of_re_mem_interior_integrableExpSet hz i
```
Since you're adding this one, you should also add all its friends (`Analytic`, `AnalyticOn`, `AnalyticWithinAt`), and also the `im_ofReal` versions.
What about assuming instead `[hÎ¼ : NeZero Î¼]` in this one? Then the next one is not needed, because typeclass inference will infer that a probability measure is not zero.
Could you instead use `analyticOn`? It is a more natural notion than `analyticOnNhd`, and both are equivalent when the set is open (as in your situation), so you're not losing anything here.

```suggestion
variable {Î© Î¹ : Type*} {m : MeasurableSpace Î©} {X : Î© â†’ â„} {Î¼ : Measure Î©} {t u v : â„}
```
It's quite confusing to have an integer named `p`.
Could you also add the very closely related fact that two identically distributed random variables have the same `complexMGF`?

```suggestion
lemma abs_complexMGF_le_mgf : |complexMGF X Î¼ z| â‰¤ mgf X Î¼ z.re := by
```

A bare `rw [integral_ofReal]` fails here because of RCLike peculiarities. I think it would be worth having a specialized version `integral_complex_ofReal` to do the rewrite directly. I have just tested, with
```
theorem integral_complex_ofReal {f : Î© â†’ â„} : âˆ« x, (f x : â„‚) âˆ‚Î¼ = (âˆ« x, f x âˆ‚Î¼) :=
  integral_ofReal
```
then `rw [integral_complex_ofReal]` works in your proof.

```suggestion
    complexMGF X Î¼ (z + Îµ) - âˆ‘ m in range n, Îµ ^ m / m ! * âˆ« Ï‰, X Ï‰ ^ m * cexp (z * X Ï‰) âˆ‚Î¼
```
(You need `open scoped Nat` for this). I'd replace all the `factorial` in the file by this.
Use `| |` instead os `abs`, here and elsewhere.
I used `abs` because I got errors with `| |` at some point, but perhaps I need to open something (which I may or may not have already opened since). I need to find out.
I get `failed to synthesize Lattice â„‚`
ok, no need to fight against this too hard. Keep `abs` where it helps.

I'm not sure I understand the articulation between this section and the next one. Below, you prove (independently of the current result) the lemma `hasDerivAt_integral_pow_mul_exp`, which directly implies the current one (taking `n = 0`), and therefore analyticity in the strip. Do you want to keep the previous results of the current section as they will have other useful applications, or should they just be removed?

I did not realize there was no link. I proved the result about the first derivative first, then other derivatives, and I did not see that I did not reuse anything from the first proof.
Removing all that material makes the proof and file much shorter!

```suggestion
the same `integrableExpSet`. -/
```
You can probably remove `[IsProbabilityMeasure Î¼']` here: at `0`, `mgf X \mu` is `1`, so nonzero, so `mgf X \mu'` is also one, so `mu'` can not be zero.

This argument feels a little bit strange to me: if they have the same `mgf` and `integrableExpSet` has nonempty interior, then `X` and `Y` are identically distributed, and then of course they have the same `complexMGF` (and not only on the vertical strip, but everywhere). I guess we don't have the fact I've used above (same mgf => identDistrib), but it looks more fundamental to me than the current statement. Unless the current statement is a lemma on the way to a proof of this result?

Etienne pointed this out too in one of the now hidden discussions above: the proof I have in mind for [equal mgf => equal distributions] is [equal mgf => equal complexMGF on a domain containing the vertical line going through 0 => equal characteristic functions => equal distributions].
Perhaps there is a more direct route I should use instead?

This is a perfectly reasonable route (I would follow the same). Maybe add comments in the docstring lemma explaining this (and in particular explain that a stronger version of the lemma can be proved once this path has been taken to its end).

I wonder if it would make sense to weaken the assumptions, just assuming that the mgf coincide on a small open interval inside `integrableExpSet` of both -- which in the end should be enough to show that they are identically distributed.

I added comments.
About the weaker assumptions: let's wait and see what would be convenient when we actually use the lemmas?

I wonder if this lemma will be enough for the proof you're describing: if `0` is on the boundary of `integrableExpSet`, then you would rather need to know that `complexMGF` coincide on the whole strip above `integrableExpSet`, not just its interior. This follows from what you have just proved, and continuity on the whole strip (which follows from dominated convergence, say, and would in any case be good to have). This can definitely wait for another PR, though!
Remove `[IsProbabilityMeasure Î¼']`?
Use `analyticOn` instead of `analyticOnNhd`.

```suggestion
    {Y : Î©' â†’ â„} (h : IdentDistrib X Y Î¼ Î¼') :
```

Don't you want to put those two on the same line?
```suggestion
    [CharZero ð•œ] {f : ð•œ â†’ ð•œ} {x : ð•œ} (h : AnalyticAt ð•œ f x) :
```

```suggestion
* `iteratedDeriv_mgf`: the n-th derivative of the mgf at `t` is `Î¼[X ^ n * exp (t * X)]`.
```
Maybe move this one to the file on `MGFAnalytic`? It is purely on the real MGF, if I understand correctly.
